sentences: Cortney Lara Tidwell was born on December 2, 1972, in Nashville, Tennessee to country singer Connie Eaton and Cliff Williamson, music producer at A&R.
He was a member of the Grand Ole Opry in the 1950s and was signed to Decca records.
In later years he was a frequent guest on the Ralph Emery show and was known as "roadmap Bob".
Though Connie remained in the music scene , she steadily withdrew and spent most of her time at home in the mid 1980s.
Connie, Cortney's mother, was diagnosed with manic depression in the early 1970s, and Cortney and the family struggled to understand and cope with her mother's illness.

In 2004, Tidwell began recording with her husband, renowned producer and acclaimed recording engineer and musician Todd Tidwell manning the studio, often contributing his own playing and songwriting to his wife's songs.

The Nashville scene consistently sang her praises and the late editor, Jim Ridley called her "Nashville’s real songbird" , She performed at Springwater with various musicians, but then began playing all the instruments herself at the same time due to raising the children and working
In addition, she has also participated in a collaborative album of reimagined songs originally recorded for and released by her grandfather's Chart Records in the 1960s.
Don't Let Stars Keep Us Tangled Up (2007, Ever Records)
Invariable Heartache (2010, City Slang) with Kurt Wagner
Featuring Tidwell's cover of R. Stevie Moore's 1978 song "I Go Into Your Mind"
